{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17656145","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17656145"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:10:49+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:10:49+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18716"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18716","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18716"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11448"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112954"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11448","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11448"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18716"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94986"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4935"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"10600"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26504"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26511"},{"type":"contributions","id":"46476"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112954","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/112954"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EOvulation requires a mid-cycle surge of luteinising hormone. In the luteal phase, further ovulation is prevented by hormonal feedback on the hypothalamic\u2013pituitary\u2013ovarian axis.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following most directly inhibits a subsequent ovulation during the luteal phase?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["High-frequency gonadotrophin-releasing hormone pulses","Rising follicle stimulating hormone secretion","Increased ovarian androgens","Declining inhibin B levels","Progesterone from the corpus luteum"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EFollowing ovulation, the corpus luteum secretes progesterone and oestradiol, which together provide negative feedback to the hypothalamus and anterior pituitary. This reduces gonadotrophin-releasing hormone drive and suppresses luteinising hormone secretion, preventing another luteinising hormone surge and thereby blocking any further ovulation within the same cycle. This mechanism underpins how combined hormonal contraception suppresses ovulation through sustained negative feedback.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHigh-frequency gonadotrophin-releasing hormone pulses\u003C/strong\u003E favour luteinising hormone secretion and would promote, rather than inhibit, the luteinising hormone rise required for ovulation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERising follicle stimulating hormone secretion\u003C/strong\u003E supports follicular recruitment and does not directly prevent the luteinising hormone surge; it is not the key luteal-phase inhibitor of ovulation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreased ovarian androgens\u003C/strong\u003E may occur in some conditions but are not the principal physiological mechanism that suppresses the luteinising hormone surge during the luteal phase.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDeclining inhibin B levels\u003C/strong\u003E primarily influence follicle stimulating hormone rather than directly suppressing the luteinising hormone surge that triggers ovulation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProgesterone from the corpus luteum\u003C/strong\u003E is the best answer because luteal progesterone (with oestradiol) reduces hypothalamic and pituitary activity, lowering luteinising hormone to levels insufficient to trigger another surge.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["High progesterone and oestradiol from the corpus luteum exert negative feedback on the hypothalamus and pituitary to suppress luteinising hormone and prevent another ovulation in the same cycle.","Combined hormonal contraception prevents ovulation primarily by sustained negative feedback on gonadotrophin release, especially suppressing the luteinising hormone surge."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019","Thomas C. Ovulation: A cellular symphony in three movements. Semin Cell Dev Biol. 2025 Jul 12;174:103634. Available from: https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S1084952125000448"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94986"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18716"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94986","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/94986"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-08T16:55:09+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-08T16:55:43+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11448"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112954"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","lin